description: From Latin collidere (“to strike or clash together”), from com- (“together”) + laedere (“to strike, dash against, hurt”); see lesion.

verbs.description: collide (third-person singular simple present collides, present participle colliding, simple past and past participle collided)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To impact directly, especially if violent.
examples: When a body collides with another, then momentum is conserved.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To come into conflict, or be incompatible.
examples: China collided with the modern world.
